Review: Loneliness and isolation are not always self imposed, and sometimes you are surrounded by joy and life and want nothing more than to be present but there's something inside of you that holds you back, and sometimes we long for connections that never existed in the first place.
I dunno guys, I watched this with some friends and we had a great time. It's the right way to watch it I think.
I liked this! I was interested the entire runtime! But I'm also the world's #1 Sam Esmail Fan (Mr. Robot my beloved), so it was just really great seeing him get this opportunity.

Perfectly fine little biopic with some stunning cinematography and acting. Honestly, I think Bradley Cooper's got the touch and I can't wait to see what he does as he continues on and takes more risks.
Not at all what I expected and extremely weird (affectionate). But I'm just not sure what this was really going for, which is holding me back from loving it. Maybe it just needs a rewatch?
Thought this ruled. Shocked to see so many people in the reviews here with a complete lack of understanding for this and what it was trying to say.
I was convinced Christian Bale was in this, so once it was clear that he wouldn't be, I looked it up and realized I was thinking of Exodus: Gods and Kings. My mistake!!

This wasy first ever Godzilla movie! So I have nothing to compare it with in regards to that, but I really loved this. Emotional beats were authentic, action was great, and characters were entertaining. (I love his little arms)
Increasingly find my relationships feeling like this. A soft, agonizing retrospective about growing up and growing apart.

Movie: The Hunger Games: The Ballad of Songbirds & Snakes
